The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Friday, August 13, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		Armed robbers looted Rs 1.3 lakh from the office of export clearing agent Mukul Badani, in Madan Dutta Lane, in the Muchipara police station area, on Thursday morning. Police said four robbers entered the office at 10.30 am. While one of them stood guard at the door, the rest ordered the office employees to hand over the money. Once they had collected the booty, they made a clean getaway. Badani and three others were present in the office then.																																																		Calcutta Metropolitan Development Authority (CMDA) officials on Thursday launched an eviction drive along the Eastern Metropolitan Bypass. Illegal structures, including shops and houses, along the road from Anandanagar to Ruby Hospital were demolished. The squatters, however, alleged that a case was pending in Calcutta High Court, and that the CMDA didnt serve any notice on them before launching the drive. 																																																		Youth Congress members demonstrated in front of Howrah mayor Gopal Mukherjees room in the Howrah Municipal Corporation (HMC) building for an hour on Thursday afternoon. They were protesting the collapse of the drainage system in the HMC area, that led to the death of six-year-old Kaynath Salim on Tuesday. 																																																		Officials of Kishalaya, a home for destitute children in Barasat, have complained to the police that two of their inmates had been missing since Monday night. Police said 10 boys had allegedly fled the home. Eight of them have been rescued. 																																																		A group of residents of Sonarpur went on the rampage at a neighbourhood nursing home on Thursday morning after the death of a seven-year-old girl, Bulti Mondal. The residents alleged that the girl died because of negligence of the nursing home authorities. Bulti was injured in the abdomen on Monday.																																																		Mayor Subrata Mukherjee has introduced a group medical insurance scheme for all 38,000 civic employees without curtailing their medical allowances. The 141 councillors, too, will be covered under the scheme. The scheme will cover medical expenses up to Rs 50,000 for every employee, his wife and two children.																																																		The Indian Chinese Association in Calcutta will start a course on the Chinese language at Sacred Heart Chinese School, on Weston Street, in central Calcutta.																																																		Calcutta Municipal Corporation (CMC) has decided to take back a 10-acre plot given to Calcutta Stock Exchange. The failure of the stock exchange authorities to start construction work on the plot in the past eight years prompted the CMC to take the decision. 																																																		Deputy commissioner of police (detective department) Peeyush Pandey will be felicitated by Balaka Sangeet Samaj at Rabindra Sadan on Friday. A cultural programme highlighting the evils of drug abuse will be held. Actress June will attend the function.To All India Allahabad Bank Officers Association for constructing a school building at Pathar Pratima, South 24-Parganas
